<subSubSection id="8DFAA6383486E4135BCDF3C90A0FBC54" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="40B24805624D785E0DCF763CE395A580" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="08D8474EDAE93E2E184706583EE263DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
This genus can be distinguished from all other genera in 
<taxonomicName id="0D68A9639F0BD652BF5C6AD50541FA6B" authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Xanthopygina">Xanthopygina</taxonomicName>
based on the combination of the following characteristics: head shape rectangular; head wider than pronotum (apomorphy; however, head size can be variable among specimens of the same species but wider than pronotum); antennomeres 7-10 transverse; left mandible with two teeth separated by deep emargination (apomorphy); labial palpomere 3 not securiform; small size eyes (apomorphy); superior marginal line of pronotal hypomeron not continuing to anterior margin; superior and inferior marginal line of hypomeron produce anterolateral angles not parallel to one other (apomorphy); postcoxal process present; elytra coloration black (except with blue metallic overtones in 
<taxonomicName id="F2ECD111EC9CAB16F4C82B446E56A35E" genus="Xa." lsidName="Xa. xanthopygus" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="xanthopygus">
<emphasis id="98DDBA1E02DB99106C1EEF8481673F95" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Xa. xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); dorsal 1/3 of metepisterstum without punctures (apomorphy; state also present in 
<taxonomicName id="FE836B58C9D3FD9A4C1F3234066148D6" genus="Ph." lsidName="Ph. mirabilis" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="mirabilis">
<emphasis id="0184D98F470D0F837574E9E20860AB8A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Ph. mirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); with more than four spines on the posterior surface of metacoxae (apomorphy; less than four in 
<taxonomicName id="049E11577992B547C849CE85D48E729B" genus="Xa." lsidName="Xa. xanthopygus" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="xanthopygus">
<emphasis id="7BB45C29BD0F2C0679074BDCE0CDBEA3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Xa. xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); tergites 3-5 with arch-like carina; and sternite 7 in males with emargination at posterior margin. For a list of characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="A8997FBAF505F6BB804179A4A3A099CC" authorityName="Kraatz" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xanthopygus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B83B634907A85423D7698BB3965EFE6E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="096AB7729AD078C90E67CA9A8BD60F90" authority="Chatzimanolis, 2021" authorityName="Chatzimanolis" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Photinopygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Photinopygus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DA3BBEFB46B59D5CF6CBC577504FD2BA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Photinopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see Table 
<tableCitation id="A619266F788F41786F10BD8EEFA6A3EF" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. List of taxonomic characters that distinguish species of Xanthopygus from Photinopygus. Numbers next to characters refers to the numbers in the data matrix. For a full list of characters and character states see Material and Methods, and for the mapping of the characters on the phylogenetic tree see Suppl. material 3." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4C02FE6978BC23F3C1313AC3D5A82848" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" tableUuid="4C02FE6978BC23F3C1313AC3D5A82848">2</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
